[2
Date: Fri, 8 May 1998 10:43:32 -0600
From: Robert P. Rennie, PhD, ABMM <rpr@bugs.uah.ualberta.ca>

I would refer you to a paper published by Anand, C.M. and ourselves in the
Canadian Journal of Infectious Diseases, Vol 8 No.6 pp.318-322
"Epidemiological investigation of _Salmonella tilene_ by pulsed-field gel
electrophoresis and polymerase chain reaction". One of the several cases
reported in this paper was a child whose family kept sugar gliders as pets.
Both the child and the sugar gliders were infected with this organism.
In addition, the same strain of Salmonella was isolated from African pygmy
hedgehogs imported into Alberta as were the sugar gliders. It raises some
important questions about whether such animals should be permitted to be
imported from one country to another without adequate examination for
enteric and other potential pathogens. In any event I hope this paper might
be useful to you.
--
Robert P. Rennie, PhD, ABMM
Microbiology and Public Health
University of Alberta Hospital
Edmonton, Alberta Canada T6G 2J2
e-mail: rpr@bugs.uah.ualberta.ca
[If the Australian Sugar Gliders and the African Pigmy Hedgehogs shared the
same salmonella serotype, it is most likely that it was because they came
through the same retail chain &/or Canadian/USA wholesaler. If so and
presumably these people carry a range of exotic and domestic species the
problem is somewhat different than posed above. I believe that the
importation of pigmy hedgehogs may have been stopped, at least by USDA.
Maybe someone more experienced in the inspection of imported exotic species
would care to enlighten us on the inspection procedures. - Mod.MHJ
